<h2>Solar Panels in Tennessee</h2>

<h3>Solar Resource and Production</h3>
<p>Tennessee's solar potential is significantly underutilized despite favorable conditions across the state. The western regions, including Memphis and surrounding counties, receive the highest solar irradiance levels at approximately 4.8 kWh/m¬≤/day, while eastern Tennessee, including Knoxville and the Appalachian foothills, averages around 4.2 kWh/m¬≤/day. Nashville and central Tennessee fall in the middle range with 4.4-4.6 kWh/m¬≤/day. These solar irradiance levels translate to excellent energy production potential, with a typical 6kW residential solar system generating between 7,200-8,400 kWh annually, depending on location, system orientation, and local weather patterns.</p>

<p>Seasonal variations in Tennessee create interesting production patterns that align well with energy consumption needs. Peak solar production occurs during summer months (May through August) when cooling demands are highest, providing natural synchronization between energy generation and consumption. Spring and fall months maintain strong production levels of 80-90% of peak capacity, while winter production typically drops to 60-70% of peak levels. However, reduced heating demands during Tennessee's mild winters mean that annual net metering credits often accumulate during shoulder seasons, providing economic benefits year-round.</p>

<p>Roof orientation and tilt angles play crucial roles in maximizing solar production in Tennessee. South-facing installations with tilt angles between 30-40 degrees typically achieve optimal performance, though southeast and southwest orientations can achieve 90-95% of optimal production. The state's relatively moderate latitude of 35-36 degrees north provides flexibility in system design, and many installations perform well even with roof-mounted systems that don't achieve perfect orientation. Ground-mounted systems offer additional optimization opportunities for properties with adequate space and favorable site conditions.</p>

